    subject: "Lake Kivu", icon: "", category: "waterway", tags: ["lake","rift"],
    easy: "In East Africa, on the western edge of Rwanda, one of the continent's Great Lakes fills a deep valley — and hides enormous amounts of gas far below its calm blue surface. Photograph the lake.",
    medium: "Word from a deep rift valley in the heart of Africa: fishermen paddle wooden boats across a huge, calm highland lake that quietly holds a fortune of natural gas locked deep in its waters. Photograph the still waters.",
    hard: "Cradled in a great crack in the earth, a vast, still highland lake lies so deep and so unusual that it stores rare gases far below, where no fish can swim, while wooden fishing boats glide out across it at dusk. Bring me the sleeping lake.",
    fact: "Lake Kivu, on the border between Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, is one of the African Great Lakes and one of only three lakes on Earth known to hold huge amounts of dissolved gas — methane and carbon dioxide — locked deep in its waters.",
