    subject: "The Simien Mountains", icon: "", category: "mountain", tags: ["unesco","escarpment"],
    easy: "In East Africa, in northern Ethiopia, a wall of jagged peaks and deep valleys carved by erosion rises to Ras Dashen, the country's highest summit. Photograph the mountains.",
    medium: "Word from a high, cool plateau in Africa where snow can fall not far from the equator: erosion has chiselled the tableland into a jagged rim of cliffs and pinnacles that plunge into vast valleys, home to grass-eating monkeys found nowhere else on Earth. Photograph the great escarpment.",
    hard: "Over millions of years, wind and rain have gnawed a high tableland into a ragged wall of cliffs, towers, and plunging gorges so lofty that snow sometimes dusts them even near the middle of the world; strange grass-grazing monkeys roam the heights. Bring me the crumbling ramparts.",
    fact: "The Simien Mountains in northern Ethiopia are a range of jagged peaks and deep valleys carved by millions of years of erosion. Ras Dashen, their highest summit at about 4,550 metres, is the tallest mountain in Ethiopia, and the whole range is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
