    easy: "In Central Africa, on Cameroon's palm-fringed coast near Kribi, the Lobé River ends its journey by tumbling in white curtains straight into the Atlantic Ocean. Photograph the waterfall.",
    medium: "Word from an Atlantic shore: a rainforest river empties over black rocks directly into the salty sea — one of the very few places on Earth where this happens — and local kings are still crowned in its spray. Photograph the water where the river meets the ocean.",
    hard: "A river fed by a great equatorial rainforest reaches the end of its run and, instead of widening into a calm mouth, spills over dark ledges straight into the open sea. Healers lead people beneath its spray to be cleansed, and new chiefs meet their ancestors here. Bring me the place where fresh water pours into salt.",
    fact: "The Lobé Falls, on the coast near Kribi in southern Cameroon, are one of the very few waterfalls on Earth that empty directly into the sea, dropping about 10–20 metres over rocks into the Atlantic Ocean and spreading up to some 270 metres wide in the rainy season.",
