    subject: "The M'zab valley town of Ghardaïa", icon: "", category: "cityscape", tags: ["unesco","desert","town"],
    easy: "In North Africa, in Algeria, a cluster of very old fortified desert towns climbs the rocky hills of the M'zab valley, each crowned by a pyramid-shaped minaret. Photograph the hilltop town.",
    medium: "Word from an oasis in the great northern desert: nearly a thousand years ago a devout Berber people built five walled towns that spiral up rocky hills around pointed watchtower minarets — a design so clever at beating the heat that architects still study it. Photograph the terraced desert town.",
    hard: "A community of Ibadi Muslims, seeking refuge, raised five fortified towns on rocky knolls above a desert wadi, each ringed by walls and centred on a mosque whose minaret doubled as a lookout. Their cool, stacked houses later inspired famous modern city planners. Bring me the terraced hill-town.",
    fact: "The M'zab valley in Algeria's northern Sahara holds five fortified hilltop towns — a 'pentapolis' — built by the Ibadi Mozabite Berbers between 1012 and 1350; Ghardaïa is the largest, and the whole valley became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1982.",
