    medium: "Word from a desert capital: here two enormous rivers, one carrying pale clay from far southern lakes and the other dark silt from eastern highlands, flow together and become the longest river on Earth. Photograph the place where the two rivers meet.",
    hard: "At a dusty capital where the desert meets the water, two mighty rivers born far apart — one in great equatorial lakes, one in distant highlands — join into a single stream that flows north for thousands of miles to the sea. Bring me the meeting of the two rivers.",
    fact: "At Khartoum, Sudan, the White Nile (from the equatorial lakes) and the Blue Nile (from the Ethiopian highlands) meet and join to form the Nile, which then flows more than 3,000 km north to Egypt and the Mediterranean Sea.",
