    subject: "The sacred mountain of Jebel Barkal", icon: "", category: "rock", tags: ["unesco","ancient","sacred"],
    easy: "In northeast Africa, in Sudan, a flat-topped sandstone mountain rises alone from the desert beside the Nile; ancient kings built temples and pyramids at its foot. Photograph the sacred mountain.",
    medium: "Word from beside a great desert river: a lone, flat-topped rock with a tall finger of stone at one end was once believed to be the home of a mighty god, so kings raised temples and pyramids around its base. Photograph the holy desert mountain.",
    hard: "Beside a great river, a solitary flat-topped crag with a slender pinnacle was believed to be the dwelling of a powerful god. For over a thousand years, rulers of two rival kingdoms built temples and steep royal tombs at its foot. Bring me the sacred desert butte.",
    fact: "Jebel Barkal is a flat-topped sandstone mountain rising about 104 m from the desert near Karima, Sudan. Ancient Egyptians and Kushites believed it was home to the god Amun and built temples and pyramids at its base; it became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2003.",
